STOCK CHARTING

In order to begin analysing stock, heres the charting plus some technical indicators such as Simple Moving Average (20 and 100), Bollinger bands (20, sd = 1), Relative Strength Index (14 days), and Moving Average Convergence Divergence (12, 25) as the technical analysis before forecasting.

# Checking whether data is Stationary or Not

plot(tesla_data)

# Transforming the data with Log

plot(log(tesla_data))

As the data has been log-transformed, we can clearly see that the series shows some upward and downward trend in a given time interval. The stock also consist of some volatility and swing. These are the signs that the stock price movement is non-stationary. Matter of fact, most of financial data is non-stationary (in which the mean, variance, autocorrelation, are not constant over time), but most of them follow random walk model with or without drift (RWM or RWD), This is due to the stock tend to having trend and inconstant variance and mean in a given period. Given that we can guess that its a random walk, which means the current value (price) is equal to its price at time (t - 1) plus a random shock (White Noise), hence we should difference the data with certain lag in order to fit ARIMA model as well see later

Checking the Autocorrelation and Partial Autocorrelation Function

This is where we check whether the current value is correlated to the past/yesterdays value.

acf_tesla = acf(tesla_data, lag.max = 320)

pacf_tesla=pacf(tesla_data, lag.max = 320)

Making the Data Stationary

tesla_data_diff= diff(log(tesla_data), lag =1) # Adjusting the mean

tesla_data_diff = na.locf(tesla_data_diff, na.rm = TRUE,
                      fromLast = TRUE) # Replacing missing values

plot(tesla_data_diff)

# Testing the Stationarity using Augmented Dickey Fuller Test. Null Hypothesis = Non-Satationary Alternative Hyp = Stationary

library(tseries)
## Warning: package 'tseries' was built under R version 4.0.5
adf <- adf.test(tesla_data, alternative = c("stationary", "explosive"), 
                k = 0)
## Warning in adf.test(tesla_data, alternative = c("stationary", "explosive"), : p-
## value greater than printed p-value
adf
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  tesla_data
## Dickey-Fuller = 1.0693, Lag order = 0, p-value = 0.99
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

Hence as p-value>0.05, we cannot RJ null and conclude that our undifferentiated tesla stock data is non-Stationary.

adf <- adf.test(tesla_data_diff, alternative = c("stationary", "explosive"), 
                k = 0)
## Warning in adf.test(tesla_data_diff, alternative = c("stationary",
## "explosive"), : p-value smaller than printed p-value
adf
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  tesla_data_diff
## Dickey-Fuller = -53.441, Lag order = 0, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

AS the p-value<0.05, we can reject null and conclude that our differentiated tesla stock data is stationary.

Plotting ACF and PACF Curves

acf_tesla  = acf(tesla_data_diff) # Determining the value of autoregressive AR(P)

pacf_tesla = pacf(tesla_data_diff) # Determining the value of moving avg MA(p)

Build the ARIMA Model

R provides simple and automatic way to generate appropriate ARIMA(p, d, q) model using auto.arima() function in forecast package with the smallest Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), Bayes Information Criterion (BIC). Here we pass in our train data, difference (d = 1),stationary = TRUE

library(forecast)
## Warning: package 'forecast' was built under R version 4.0.5
set.seed(100)
arima_model <- auto.arima(tesla_data_diff, stationary = TRUE, ic = c("aicc", "aic", "bic"), 
                          trace = TRUE)

Fitting the model and forecasting

arima <- arima(tesla_data_diff, order = c(0, 0, 0))
summary(arima)
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = tesla_data_diff, order = c(0, 0, 0))
## 
## Coefficients:
##       intercept
##          0.0019
## s.e.     0.0007
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.00124:  log likelihood = 5551.43,  aic = -11098.86
## 
## Training set error measures:
##                         ME       RMSE        MAE  MPE MAPE     MASE        ACF1
## Training set -2.621109e-15 0.03520671 0.02401454 -Inf  Inf 0.688105 0.003178749
forecast_tesla <- forecast(arima, h = 365)
plot(forecast_tesla)

checkresiduals(arima)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(0,0,0) with non-zero mean
## Q* = 8.8644, df = 9, p-value = 0.4499
## 
## Model df: 1.   Total lags used: 10

Here our forecast for 365 days ahead shows straight line. This is due to nature of arima forecasting tends to be mean reversion. The Ljung Box test shows that the model residuals are non-autocorrelated, suggesting theres no heterocedasticity problem and the model is good, otherwise we might consider GARCH model. # Forecating for 2021

arima1 = arima(log(tesla_data[1:2650]), order=c(0,1,0))
